1000 words a day isn't bad.
That 150K I did is ~ 1667/day. It ranged from streaks of 300-500 words, to a few weekends where I got 12K over two days.

One thing I do on nights where I have little inspiration but some motivation is to work in chunks of 50-200 words.
If you're good at dialogue, sketch that first. Action or descriptions? Do those.
Once you have the skeleton of a scene, the rest gets easier. Then do the same with the next scene, revise to tie to the previous scene.

Don't let any one day drag you down.

Not bad at all for a first go around. Glad to see you didn't go too overboard on exposition before getting into it. Definitely seems like there'll be room to fill things in later.

A quick technical point, the vast majority of revolvers (basically anything from a mainstream US manufacturer) is not going to have a safety. The 'safety mechanism' is built into the trigger, in that it's either a single action (requires the hammer to be pulled back), a double action (hammer can be cocked and fired by a single trigger pull, but it's a long and heavy squeeze), or a combination of the two.
On the bright side, this actually makes for a more dramatic scene, as it's a nominally more involved process, e.g.:

>In a single swift motion, you drop the beer bottle onto the bed and reach from the .44 revolver on your nightstand, (optional)thumbing the hammer back with well practiced ease (/optional/).

or

>Standing up, you check the check to make sure the gun is still loaded, silently pressing the cylinder back into the frame and drawing the hammer back. Cautiously, you make your way....

>Turning to exit the room you sigh, wiping the sweat from your brow and riding the hammer forward on your .44.

>Grasping the doorknob, you swing the closet door open so hard it practically flies off the hinges. You draw down on the intruder, the revolver's cylinder indexing as you draw the hammer back.

As >>27765739 said, little details make a big difference.

LOL, a double/Single action. It can operated either way. Double action for faster, simpler, follow up shots, and single action for improved accuracy, with a lighter, shorter, trigger pull. DA/SA triggers are the norm in most S&W or Ruger modern full frame revolvers. Classic or target revolvers tend to be single action (and don't have swing-away cylinders). Concealed carry revolvers tend to be double action (for simplicity, and because they're often 'hammerless' (the hammer is inside the frame of the gun) for ease of draw from concealment.
